If you must protect each cell/tile individually rather than in a group, the solution seems obvious: 

&#128073;&#127997; When you populate `ObjectCell[][] cells`, you also populate a parallel `ReentrantLock[][] locks`. 

```java
if (cells[i][j] == null) {
    cells[i][j] = new ObjectCell(jpeg_quality);
    locks[i][j] = new ReentrantLock();
}
```

Your code:

```java
synchronized (cells[i][j]) 
{
    cells[i][j].update(subimage);
}
```

… becomes:

```java
locks[i][j].lock();
try
{
    cells[i][j].update(subimage);
}
finally
{
    locks[i][j].unlock();
}
```


  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/77176727/642706

The most straightforward way to convert code from `synchronized` to `ReentrantLock`, if you can modify the class being locked, is to add a `ReentrantLock` member to the object that was previously `synchronized`. To simplify the example, given a `Tile` class like this:

```java
public class Tile {
    public void update() {
        // ...
    }
}
```

and a usage of it like this:

```java
synchronized (tile) {
    tile.update();
}
```

It can be modified this way:

```java
import java.util.concurrent.locks.Lock;
import java.util.concurrent.locks.ReentrantLock;

public class Tile {
    public final Lock lock = new ReentrantLock();

    public void update() {
        // ...
    }
}
```

and used like this:

```java
tile.lock.lock();
try {
    tile.update();
} finally {
    tile.lock.unlock();
}
```

If the `Tile` class cannot be modified, you can either keep a parallel array of `ReentrantLock` instances, or refactor to wrap the `Tile` and `ReentrantLock` together in another class.

There are some other things you might want to consider for your use case.

# Avoiding client-side locking

This pattern of the code accessing an object acquiring a lock on it is sometimes known as _client-side locking_, because it is the client of the locked object that is responsible for acquiring the lock, rather than the locked object itself. This practice is often [discouraged](https://wiki.sei.cmu.edu/confluence/display/java/LCK11-J.+Avoid+client-side+locking+when+using+classes+that+do+not+commit+to+their+locking+strategy) due to a major drawback: it relies on _all_ usages of the object to correctly and consistently implement the locking strategy. This makes it very hard to reason about the thread-safety of the class, as it can only be understood by considering every use of the class throughout the code. As an example of how this can cause a problem: if the code is updated from `synchronized` to using `ReentrantLock` in one place, but not in others, then the mutual exclusion property will be broken.

As an alternative, the `Tile` class could take responsibility for locking itself, documenting its thread-safety guarantees in terms of its properties, rather than its implementation:

```java
import java.util.concurrent.locks.Lock;
import java.util.concurrent.locks.ReentrantLock;

public class Tile {
    private final Lock lock = new ReentrantLock();

    public void update() {
        lock.lock();
        try {
            // ...
        } finally {
            lock.unlock();
        }
    }
}
```

It can then be used in a more straightforward way:

```java
tile.update(); // no need to lock here
```

This is a simplified example, and in the real `Tile` class, other methods would also need to be modified to acquire the lock as needed.

# Fine-grained vs. coarse-grained locking

In the case of a composite object, where one object (in this case, `TileManager`) contains a collection of internal objects that are completely encapsulated and not exposed to other classes (in this case, `Tile`), there&#39;s a choice to make when operating concurrently on the internal collection: you can either lock each item in the collection independently (fine-grained locking), or you can lock the entire collection (coarse-grained locking). These have tradeoffs, and the best option depends on the specific use case. Fine-grained locking, as in this example, allows multiple threads to concurrently access different parts of the collection, which helps to avoid a long-running process preventing other threads from accessing elements that it isn&#39;t currently affecting. The main drawback to be aware of is the risk of deadlock if there is a thread that needs to lock multiple elements at the same time. There is also the potential for different behaviour when there is high contention. The `processImage` method could become blocked several times, waiting to acquire locks on individual tiles. It might be more desirable to allow it to acquire a single coarse-grained lock and complete the iteration of `tiles` without the risk of further blocking. This really depends on the specifics of the application, and must be considered with the context of the other uses of the data.

